{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340582986/1920072001/0425.xml":{"full_text":"COLLECTOR RECEIVES\nPROCEEDS OF SALE OF\nCONFISCATED AUTOS\nChecks amounting to K>, 160.50 were j\nturned over to John D. McNeel, collector\ncif internal revenue, yesterday by N. L\nPierce, federal prohibition enforcement\nagent, which is a part of the proceeds se- I\ncured from the sale of several automo\nWARNING\nIt kwglnt y\u00bbur t\u00bb\u00ab1> rwvlir do not\nMao to pnrttU.w\n6t mlmral IaxiIItm Ju*t try KOROLAX,\nttf*. fwithk wholesome. B\u00abt and *<x*\nfa-thesl. OWlinah'.e at busy druggists. r*rrj\nKsrsks ls r^Ut f<x n*nj aiUMOtiu\n{ndndirtc consflytion htadaebss. dizzy\nbsd brwstK \u25a0srr\u00abwi\u00absi*.-dW*\u00abptf\u00bb. trrt'tv\nb*n orrmmt\n\u00ae*w*tty. w\u00ae***! a*4 physical dallMaa.\nbilea and other property confiscated by\nthe government In prohilbtlon cases.\nThis report does not include all of the\ncars seized by the local office, accord\ning to Mr. Pierce, nor any of the cars\nconfiscated in other sections of the state.\nIt is an accumulation of sales by the\nBirmingham office, it is stated.\nIt is estimated that property seized all\nover the state when sold will probably\nshow a total of $6,000. Many of the ve\nhicles confiscated during the past six\nmonths are tied up pending the outcome\nof litigation which has arisen since the\nseizures, stated Mr. Pierce.\nAmong the property sold recent!*, the\nproceeds of which were turned over to\nMr. McNeel yesterday, were seven auto\nmobiles, two mules, one horse, two\nwagons and a quantity of harness.\nThe average yearly wage paid to the\nentire number of railroad workers in\nthe United States today is $1,280.30 for\na normal working year of 306 eight\nhour days.\nDon't Feed 40c Cotton to\nthe Boll Weevil!\nUSE\nGRASSELLI\nCalcium Arsenate\nMade to conform strictly to Government\nspecifications. Used extensively by Doctor\nCoad at the Tallulah, La., Laboratory. Car\nried in stock at Birmingham, Gadsden,\nSelma and Dothan, Ala., for prompt ship\nment.\nIt is necessary to place orders ahead, as\nsupply will not equal the demand. W,\nfor literature. J\nTHE GRASSELI/\nCHEMICAL COMPANY\nBirmingham, Gadsden, Seim*,\n\u2014ar\nJothan, Ala.\nV\nhe Wire Chief Guards\nYour Service\n^I i S is tKe wire chief. This important factor in telephone\noperating is unknown to the subscriber but the task he per\nforms makes continuous telephone service possible.\nThe wire chief and his assistants are the clearing house for\ntrouble. They must see that the telephone lines, both inside and\noutside the exchange, are kept constantly in good working order.\nDay and night the work of testing the lines and apparatus goes\non. Complaints are promptly followed up and breaks are often re\npaired before you know of the trouble or have been inconvenienced.\nIf you leave your receiver off the hook, if lightning strikes a cable,\nor if any one of a hundred things over which we have no control,\nhappens to your telephone line, the wire chief finds the nature and\nlocation of the trouble and sees that it is repaired.\nIf there is a weak point in your line he knows it and watches it.\nHis vigilance often prevents troubles. Frequently service is re\nstored before you are aware of its interruption.\nBut the wire chief is no wizard and because there are many\ntroubles he cannot know about until they are reported by the sub\nscriber, we ask you to make prompt report to the complaint desk.\nWe need your co-operation in reporting troubles to us as much\nas we need it in rendering the service. Often people complain to\nneighbors and friends about the telephone service, but do not report\nit to us. Your friends may be interested but they cannot help you.\nWe can help you if you will make reports to us; certainly we are\nvitally interested.\nThe wire chiefs desk is one of the many marvelous things you\nwill see when you visit the telephone exchange to get better ac\nquainted with us.\nGeo. R.- Knox, Jr., District Manager\nSOUTHERN BELL TELEPHONE\nAND TELEGRAPH COMPANY\nBusiness Outlook Good in\nSpite of Adverse Factors\nStrangulation of Transportation and Credit Cause Suffer\ning and Both Could Be Easily Remedied, According\nto Theodore H. Price\u2019s Business Review\nBy THEODORE H. PRICE\nNew York, July 19.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The centrifugal pull of ec\ncentricity has prevented the nomination of a vote getter by the\nmotley political convention gathered at Chicago and all that\nneed now be said in regard to the economic significance of the^\nj third party movement is that it has none. The atmosphere/fs:\ncleared for a clean cut battle between Cox and Harding,/and\nwhoever is elected the country will be safe and is certain \\fi have\na newspaperman for President. This certainty sub/ectively\n{considered inspires the hope that newsprint maybe cheaper.\nI Business generally is suffering from an\n'avoidable strangulation of transportation\nand credit. Factories are shutting down\nbecause they can not get coal and raw\nI material or ship the goods that they pro\nduce. Merchants are deterred from buy\ning to replenish their exhausted stocks\nbecause money is high and difficult to\nborrow on any terms.\nDespite the enormous profits that the\nfederal reserve banks are making as a\nresult of which some of them have al\nready accumulated a surplus equal tel\ntheir capital, there has been no redrJ~\n/I\nSpeedy Relief\nFrom Habitual\nConstipation\n/.omacn, oaa oreatn,\n|\u00b0.n* Jkmins in back and under\nr\u2019l)s on riBht side.\nOder bladj# a*\nThe liver is the Iar*e^nnd,\nportant organ in the byfc caUges\nliver refuses to act- uoqjq.u\u201e.\nstipation, biliouanej^^^ bhd' br fh;\ngestion, gas\nJysr\nshoulder u.ao- w.,d cold influensa or\nThese \u00abyn^ryibitB unles3 'correctcd im.\nother serous\nliver places an extra burden\n.,/na?T?ys, which overtaxes them and\n^Hrbjood to absorb and carry into\nLK# CS n *mPurif*es that the liver and\n\u00bby^ave failed to eliminate,\nr 1 vyT^ you ^rea^ the liver alone, you treat\n/a third of your trouble, and that is\nof you have to take purgatives every few\nghts. Calomel or other ordinary laxatives\nnot go far enough. If you would treat\nyqur kidneys and blood while treating the\nliver, you would put your entire system in\norder and frequent purgatives would then\nbe unnecessary.\nDr. W. L. Hitchcock many years ago\nrecognized these important facts, and after\nmuch study and research, compounded what\nis now known as Dr. Hitchcock\u2019s Liver,\nKidney and Blood Powders, three medicines\ncombined in one. This was the Doctor\u2019s fa\nvorite prescription for many years, being\nused by his patients with marked success.\nIt is a harmless vegetable remedy that will\nnot make you sick, and you may eat any\nthing you like/ while taking it.\nGet a large tin box from your druggist or\ndealer for 25c, under his personal guaran\ntee that it will give relief, tone up the liver,\nstimulate the kidneys to healthy action and\nthereby purify the blood. If your dealer will\nnot supply you, it will be mailed direct\nby the Hitchcock Medicine Co., Atlanta,\nGa., upon receipt of price.\u2014Adv.\ntion in rediscount rate?. jpnterprise >s m\nconsequence restrjfifl*M and business\nthrottled by the A/dciiity in obtaining\ncredit, and of federA1\nreserve o(ticyir%^K^lc^\u00bb if it does not\norder, sug^M 4pBt the member banKs\nshould pr^P* a discrimination in mak\ning loanj^K1 is extremely irritating and\ndepres\u00aby^B5p the self-respecting business\nman^^P^e^ls that when the nation is\nnot,^^Par the* demand for his goods\nsh^Hr determine whether they are es\nK\u2019r not.\nCURIOUS PATERNALISM\nw*he federal reserve disposition toward\na meticulous paternalism is curiously ex\nemplified in an order issued by the Chi\ncigo bank forbidding any clerk who gets\nless than $125 a month to marry without\nconsulting the chief clerk, the apparent,\nthough mistaken assumption being that\nmatrimony is among the non-essentials.\nThe transportation tie-up is almost as\nfactitious as the shortage of credit. The\nrailroads are gasping for financial breath\nwhile the interstate commerce commis\nsion waits upon the labor board to de\ncide the wage question before announcing\nthe advance in rates which every one\nknows will have to be allowed.\nMeantime we must wait. Goods are\nawaiting shipment, coal is awaiting car\nriage anti an increasing number of men\nare awaiting work while the agencies or\ngovernment that have been set up to fa\ncilitate business debate and deliberate.\nAs to coal there seems to be no doubt\nthat nearly all the trouble is due to the\nshortage of transportation. The New\nYork Central is advertising an increase of\n23 per cent over 1913 In Its coal loadings\nfor the first five months of 1920. Other\nstatistics indicate that there would be\nno shortage in production if cars were\npromptly discharged. The geological\nsurvey, for instance, reports a bituminous\nproduction of 232,272,000 tons for the first\n15j working days of 1920, approximately\n44,173,000 tons more than the production\nduring the same time in 1919.\nCOAL OUT OF GROUND\nIn a report issued July 16 the interstate\ncommerce commission asserts that\ni \u201cloaded cars in the hands of speculators\nI are clogging the terminals of the rail\nroads at virtually every point east of the\nMississippi river, and are preventing the\nI movement to destination of thousands of\ni other loaded cars.\u2019\u2019 This looks like the\nusual attempt to blame it on the spec\nulator, but it is reassuring nevertheless\nto know that the coal is out of the\nground, and is to be had if it can be\nmoved. Precedent justifies the belief that\nit will soon be moved, and that the trans\nportation tie-up will shortly be untied,\nfor the railroad managers and the inter\nstate commerce commission realize that\nthere is to be an election next autumn\nand that the American people will not\nmuch longer tolerate the intolerable.\nUpon the foregoing premise it may be\naffirmed with confidence that business\nconditions are sound. Good crops are be\ning harvester or in prospect. Future\ntrading in wheat was resumed in Chi\n'cago July 15 on the basis of for the\nj December option. The price has since de\nclined about 10 cents a bushel on the\nbrilliant crop outlook. A sharp decline in\nforeign exchange is interpreted as mean\ning a continuance of heavy exports. Cot\nton has advanced upon the theory that\nEuropean takings next year wrill ap\nproach the pre-war normal and absorb\nthe present surplus plus the prospective\ncrop which continues to Improve. A tre\nmendous apple crop and a shortage of\nbarrels is predicted. There is much talk\nof a curtailment in the demand for motor\ncars and tires, but it is an old story\nof which the public has become incredu\nlous, although it must be admitted that\nthe business of selling automobiles on\ntime has been checked by the scarcity\nof credit, and there and there have been\nRub-My-Tism is a great pain killer.\nIt relieves pain and soreness caused\nby Rheumatism, Neuralgia, Sprains,\netc.\nIt is also a powerful antiseptic; it\ncuts, cures old so^es, tetter, etc.\u2014\nAdv.\nOFFENSIVE BREATH\nCALLS FOR CALOMEL\nTAKE A CALOTAB\nThe Nausealess Calomel Tab*\nlet That Is Purified From\nDanger and Unpleasant Ef\nfects.\nDo you ever have a bad taste in your\nmouth in the morning, heavy breath, coated\ntongue, headache, nervousness, with a let\ndown feeling? You need calomel, nothing\nelse will cleanse your liver thoroughly. Try\nCalotabs, the nausealess tablet that ia de\nlightful to take and delightful in effect. On*\ntablet at bedtime, with a swallow of water,\ni\u2014that\u2019s all. No taste, no griping, no salts,\nnor nausea. Wake up in the morning feel\ning like a two-year-old, bright, cheerful, en\nergetic and with a hearty appetite for\nbreakfast. Eat what you please\u2014no dan\nger. Calotabs are so entirely delightful Vo\ntake and so pleasant in effect that the